WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.140
To feel why that matters, step back into

00:00:02.140 --> 00:00:03.420
the world that made these prints.

00:00:04.200 --> 00:00:06.520
The "dance of death," the danse macabre,

00:00:07.040 --> 00:00:09.660
was already an old idea — a procession

00:00:09.660 --> 00:00:11.160
of the living led away by the dead,

00:00:11.160 --> 00:00:13.780
painted across the walls of charnel houses

00:00:13.780 --> 00:00:15.980
so a whole town could file past it.

00:00:16.700 --> 00:00:18.620
Its message was blunt and democratic:

00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:21.180
whatever your rank, Death is the great

00:00:21.180 --> 00:00:24.020
equalizer, and every class distinction is

00:00:24.020 --> 00:00:26.940
wiped out the moment he takes your hand.

00:00:26.940 --> 00:00:29.320
Holbein inherited that idea — and

00:00:29.320 --> 00:00:30.900
sharpened every edge of it.

00:00:31.080 --> 00:00:33.340
He was working in Basel in the 1520s,

00:00:33.640 --> 00:00:35.320
a city right on the fault line of

00:00:35.320 --> 00:00:37.560
the Reformation, and what he made was less

00:00:37.560 --> 00:00:40.160
a gentle memorial than what scholars call

00:00:40.160 --> 00:00:43.040
a reformist satire: the old allegory,

00:00:43.320 --> 00:00:44.020
re-pointed.
